-
	Poem of Exodus Omega One
-
	-
		Philosophy
	-
		-
			This is the poem of Exodus Omega One.
		-
	-
		Principles
	-
		-
			Chapter 1 - The Peace
		-
			-
				Chapter 1 - The Peace: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now the child and the traveler lived in peace for a time.
				-
		-
			Chapter 2 - The Test
		-
			-
				Chapter 2 - The Test: Verse 1
			-
				-
					And the child grew and thrived in the home of the traveler, and learned of many
					amazing arts.
				-
			-
				Chapter 2 - The Test: Verse 2
			-
				-
					Now the traveler noticed that among all the arts, it was the great art that the
					child possesed a particular affinity for.
				-
			-
				Chapter 2 - The Test: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Indeed, the great art was common to the elite among the people in those latter
					days, for it was an elemental fixture of their literacy.
				-
			-
				Chapter 2 - The Test: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Yet the traveler saw fit that the child should possess a more profound
					reverence for that by which man may command matter, that by which man may play
					God.
				-
			-
				Chapter 2 - The Test: Verse 5
			-
				-
					Thus when the child had come upon a decade did the traveler, upon waking from a
					visit unto their past upon the road of dreams, take the child before the waters
					of the forest so as to give unto them a trial befitting of the great art.
				-
			-
				Chapter 2 - The Test: Verse 6
			-
				-
					And in the depths of the forest did the traveler capsize their vessel and cast
					it into a pit.
				-
		-
			Chapter 3 - The Problem
		-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Problem: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now the child had a penchant for mischief, and lay turned down in the waters to
					the horror of the traveler, only then to jump up to their amusement and the
					traveler's annoyance.
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Problem: Verse 2
			-
				-
					Yet only upon rising from the water did they see that the traveler had forsaken
					their vessel, and they cried out, and they protested unto the traveler "will
					you not fetch the vessel, as I am too weak to do myself, for how else shall we
					return home?"
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Problem: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the traveler said unto the child "see that you are a human among the
					elements, thus you need not to possess great strength of body, for you shall
					take control over the strength of nature so as to acquire the means by which we
					may depart."
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Problem: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Knowing any further protest was in vain did the child take heed of the
					traveler's words, and took note of the locale.
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Problem: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And the child waded in the waters, and saw that the waters parted upon their
					body, and parted also upon the stones they stood upon.
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Problem: Verse 6
			-
				-
					Thus the child began to build a fort from the stones upon the river bed, and
					behold, as the waters parted upon the fort did they flow unto the pit.
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Problem: Verse 7
			-
				-
					Yet the vessel would not rise, for the earth of the pit swallowed up the
					waters.
				-
			-
				Chapter 3 - The Problem: Verse 8
			-
				-
					And in despair did the child slump against the dirt in defeat, and weep.
				-
		-
			Chapter 4 - The Solution
		-
			-
				Chapter 4 - The Solution: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now the traveler said unto the child, "see that you have indeed taken nature's
					strength for your own, and see that you have learned that nature is a devious
					and fickle beast, but know this, neither your tears nor anyone else's shall
					fill this pit nor heal any wound".
				-
			-
				Chapter 4 - The Solution: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the traveler wiped the tears from the child's eye and said unto them
					"therefore, do not dare to give up".
				-
			-
				Chapter 4 - The Solution: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And with their eyes dry did the child rise again, and stood for a moment in
					thought.
				-
			-
				Chapter 4 - The Solution: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And the child retrieved yet more stones from the riverbed, and placed them unto
					the floor of the pit.
				-
			-
				Chapter 4 - The Solution: Verse 5
			-
				-
					Behold, the waters held their place, and the vessel rose!
				-
			-
				Chapter 4 - The Solution: Verse 6
			-
				-
					Thus did the child pass the trial, and the traveler said unto them, "now
					reflect upon this day, and know from this day forth that no matter how dire the
					situation there shall always be a way up."
				-
		-
			Chapter 5 - The Knowledge
		-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Knowledge: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now in the days following their departure from the forest and unto their home
					did the traveler teach the child further regarding the great art, and the child
					became strong in it.
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Knowledge: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And beyond the sight of the traveler did the child return unto the forest many
					times so as to reflect further upon the great art.
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Knowledge: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And by the time two suns had come and gone since the child had passed the trial
					did they become so strong in the great art that they employed its might to
					forge for themselves a third eye.
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Knowledge: Verse 4
			-
				-
					However, beyond the horizon the tyrant made war with an uprising led by the
					prophet.
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Knowledge: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And having seen the power of meta as their forces fled the freedom fighters,
					the tyrant knew that the traveler might know its secrets also, and so conspired
					to come against the traveler for the sake of an invincible weapon, and directed
					their wrath to do what they would with the village.
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Knowledge: Verse 6
			-
				-
					Meanwhile, the child, having grown strong in the arts, took of the humble funds
					raised with them to allot for themselves a platform upon which to perform, and
					to commision their favorite sweets shop to cater the audience, so that, on the
					next anniversary of the traveller's birth, they would present a display of
					their learnings unto the people of the village, as a surpise gift of gratitude
					unto their teacher. 
				-
			-
				Chapter 5 - The Knowledge: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And for the coming performance did the child begin to weave a narrative in
					which to contextualize it, working in mirrors of all that they knew and all
					whom they knew.
				-
		-
			Chapter 6 - The Cry
		-
			-
				Chapter 6 - The Cry: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now the child was pure of heart, innocent, and ignorant of the wicked truth of
					life, knowing not the law of this world, to kill or be killed, for the strong
					eat the weak.
				-
			-
				Chapter 6 - The Cry: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And as the child reflected upon the great art did they play together with the
					creatures of the forest.
				-
			-
				Chapter 6 - The Cry: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And one day did the child deliver a small creature struggling in the waters of
					the river unto its bank.
				-
			-
				Chapter 6 - The Cry: Verse 4
			-
				-
					BUT BEFORE THE CHILD'S EYES, THE VERY CREATURE UNTO WHOM THE CHILD HAD GIVEN
					NEW LIFE, SNUFFED OUT THE LIFE OF ANOTHER UPON THE BANK, AND THE CHILD KNEW THE
					LAW AND ITS INIQUITY FOR THE FIRST TIME, AND THEY CRIED OUT IN HORROR.
				-
		-
			Chapter 7 - The Love
		-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Love: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now in the days following the child's cry did they seek console from the
					traveler.
				-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Love: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the traveler inquired if the child had loved this creature who had perished
					before them.
				-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Love: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Now the child stood perplexed, for it was their understanding that this word
					"love" referred to an erotic sort of passion, not the sort of thing that one,
					save for a deviant, might have towards a beast.
				-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Love: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And the traveler said that one who would say that physical passion is not
					merely one of many expressions of love, but is love itself, is spiritually
					bankrupt.
				-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Love: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And the traveler recited a story in the book of the old God from three thousand
					suns ago, of how the child of God performed the greatest act of love ever
					known, not an act of lustful passion that lasted a single night, but an act of
					self sacrifice that echoed across all of time.
				-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Love: Verse 6
			-
				-
					Now the child stood amazed before the nobility of the child of God, and
					expressed a desire to emulate such generosity unto all.
				-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Love: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And the traveler said that if the child truly loves this world, then they
					should not die, but should live, and express their love unto its people in
					life.
				-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Love: Verse 8
			-
				-
					Now the traveler asked if the child truly understood love, and the child was
					unsure.
				-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Love: Verse 9
			-
				-
					And so the traveler, who had forged the child by their hand as the old God was
					said to have done unto the children of the garden, yet loved this child such
					that no sin could ever sever or revoke it, lifted the child into a heartfelt
					embrace, and the traveler repeated their question, and the child understood.
				-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Love: Verse 10
			-
				-
					"Indeed", said the traveler, "love is the greatest force in the universe."
				-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Love: Verse 11
			-
				-
					"And...", said the traveler, "it is by the love that you have for this world
					that you shall be a light unto it, in this my faith is absolute."
				-
			-
				Chapter 7 - The Love: Verse 12
			-
				-
					And so the traveler and the child went unto the table so as to bring that night
					to a close.
				-
		-
			Chapter 8 - The Visit
		-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The Visit: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now As the child and the traveler sat before the table was their door visted by
					a strange figure, who, though an elder of the child, appeared as a mirror image
					unto them.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The Visit: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the traveler recoiled in horror, for they knew the strange figure's
					identity, but as this figure had recited the traveler's name did the child
					welcome them into their home, for any friend of the traveler was a friend of
					the child, and the child went to retrieve a gift for their guest.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The Visit: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Now while the child was away did the traveler confront the strange figure,
					pleading for the child not to know the terror of this world.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The Visit: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Yet the strange figure had fated the child to leave, and the traveler protested
					to no avail, for they knew this strange figure's decision was absolute.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The Visit: Verse 5
			-
				-
					Now the child returned unto the table bearing their gift, and the strange
					figure ate of it, and remarked that its sweetness emulated that of the child, a
					remark the child found flattering yet odd.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The Visit: Verse 6
			-
				-
					And the strange figure asked of the traveler if they had meant what they said,
					that love was the greatest force in the unvierse, and the traveler froze in
					fear of the eavesdropper.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The Visit: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And the strange figure said unto the child and the traveler: "surely, as you
					are aware that love can motivate good and evil alike, it is not the greatest
					force in the unvierse, for that title belongs only to that which sits at the
					core of God's heart, the way up, whatever that might happen to be, beacuse that
					is what love ultimately answers to."
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The Visit: Verse 8
			-
				-
					And seeing fit now to depart did the strange figure place their hand upon the
					child so as to bid them farewell.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The Visit: Verse 9
			-
				-
					BUT IN A FIT OF RAGE, THE TRAVELER STRUCK THE STRANGE FIGURE OFF THEIR FEET,
					AND THE HOUSE SHOOK AS THE STRANGE FIGURE COLLIDED WITH AND SEARED THE FLOOR,
					AND THE CHILD CRIED OUT IN SHOCK.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The Visit: Verse 10
			-
				-
					So, the strange figure acknowledged that they had overstayed their welcome, and
					went at last to depart, but as they stood before the door did they say unto the
					child: "know this little one, the world, your future, is filled with twists and
					turns, ups and downs, hopes and dreams, death and despair, but there is one
					thing you must remember, no matter what happens."
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The Visit: Verse 11
			-
				-
					And the child paused, and the strange figure said unto them: "remember that you
					are good, my child, always remember this."
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The Visit: Verse 12
			-
				-
					And the strange figure left with that, and after the door had closed did the
					child look through the window only to see that the strange figure had vanished.
				-
			-
				Chapter 8 - The Visit: Verse 13
			-
				-
					AND IN A VIOLENT FIT DID THE TRAVELER CURSE EVERYTHING IN SIGHT, AND THE CHILD
					FLED UNTO THEIR QUARTERS, AND THE TRAVELER WEPT FOR THE CHILD.
				-
		-
			Chapter 9 - The Alert
		-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Alert: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now the traveler knew that tragedy approached, but knew neither when nor how,
					until upon the next anniversary of their birth, the very day the child was to
					perform their arts in the traveller's name, the traveller heard upon a wave of
					light that the wrath of the tyrant descending upon the village.
				-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Alert: Verse 2
			-
				-
					Thus did the traveler, after arming themselves, with both conventional and
					unconventional agents, go to fetch the child, but could not locate them, and
					the traveler ran from their home, desperately calling the child's name.
				-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Alert: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Now as it happened the child, having kept their plans hidden from the traveller
					that the day might not be spoiled, sent their friends to fetch the guest of
					honor, but as the two searches met did the traveler make known their distress,
					demanding to know where the child was.
				-
			-
				Chapter 9 - The Alert: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And the children, noting the expression upon the traveler's face, pointed in
					the direction of the market square, and the traveler ran off, but as they
					darted past the children, they turned for a brief moment to face them, knowing
					what was to be their fate, and they whispered "I am... so sorry...".
				-
		-
			Chapter 10 - The Performance
		-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Performance: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now the traveler entered what appeared to be a vacant area in the center of the
					village, only to be met with thunderous applause from the townsfolk, and the
					child, taking that as their cue, ascended to the stage.
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Performance: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the traveler, seeing the child, called out to them, and the child,
					surrounded by great creations of their own design, responded in a grandiose
					tone so as to greet their guest of honor, but their smile began to fade as the
					traveler charged towards the stage, violently shoving audience members to the
					ground in the process.
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Performance: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And as the traveler lept onto the stage was the child taken aback as the
					traveler towered over them, and the child, shaken but hoping that it was merely
					a misunderstanding, said nervously unto their guest "this... this is... for
					you...".
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Performance: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Now the traveler, snapping out of their terror for just long enough to realize
					what this all was, did acknowledge that it was an impressive display, but
					immediately reverted to a stern tone, insisting that the child must leave with
					them at once.
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Performance: Verse 5
			-
				-
					But the child protested, demanding to know where they were going and why it was
					so important that the traveler had to spit their gift in their face, but the
					traveler, to avoid throwing the entire crowd into a panic, refused to say.
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Performance: Verse 6
			-
				-
					Now as they child continue to protest did the traveler seize them by the hand,
					before dragging them kicking and screaming off the stage.
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Performance: Verse 7
			-
				-
					NOW AS THE CHILD'S HOPE FOR THIS DAY GAVE WAY TO A WELL OF TEARS DID THEY, IN
					THEIR MISERY, CRY UNTO THE TRAVELER "I HATE YOU!"
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Performance: Verse 8
			-
				-
					And the traveler paused together with the whole of the crowd in shock, and
					though they struggled to keep their composure, they began to cry, and as they
					turned to face the child did the child, caught off guard by their own tone,
					saying "I... I did not mean..."
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Performance: Verse 9
			-
				-
					But as the child stuttered their apology did the traveler take note of an
					unusual hue reflecting off the child's face, and of the fact that something in
					the sky had caught the child's attention.
				-
			-
				Chapter 10 - The Performance: Verse 10
			-
				-
					And the child, awestruck, asked "what... is that?"
				-
		-
			Chapter 11 - The Terror
		-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Terror: Verse 1
			-
				-
					NOW AS THE SKY GREW BRIGHTER DID THE TRAVELER, IN A PANIC, TACKLE THE CHILD TO
					THE GROUND SO AS TO SHIELD THE CHILD WITH THEIR BODY, AS THE SKY LIT UP IN A
					BRILLIANT FLASH, AND THE EARTH SHOOK.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Terror: Verse 2
			-
				-
					AND THE CHILD STRUGGLED UNDER THE TRAVELER'S WEIGHT, BEFORE THE TRAVELER
					PAINSTAKINGLY LIFTED THEMSELVES UP TO REVEAL THAT THEY WERE BLEEDING, AND THE
					CHILD AND THE TRAVELER LOOKED AROUND TO SEE THAT THE MARKET SQUARE HAD BEEN
					LAID TO WASTE, THE PEOPLE ALL EITHER DEAD OR INJURED.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Terror: Verse 3
			-
				-
					AND AS THE CHILD ATTEMPTED TO SCREAM DID THE TRAVELER MUFFLE THEM BEFORE DIVING
					WITH THE CHILD INTO AN ALLEY AND DRAWING THEIR WEAPON, AND AS THEY TOOK COVER
					WAS THE MARKET SQUARE SWARMED BY THE WRATH OF THE TYRANT.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Terror: Verse 4
			-
				-
					NOW THE TRAVELER HELD THE CHILD CLOSE AS THEY SNUCK THROUGH THE ALLEY TOWARDS A
					SEWER LINE, THAT THEY MIGHT MAKE THEIR ESCAPE, BUT JUST AS THEY NEARED THE
					ENTRANCE WAS THE PATH OBSTRUCTED BY A SOLDIER.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Terror: Verse 5
			-
				-
					AND THE TRAVELER SET THE CHILD ON THE GROUND, BEHIND A SMALL PILLAR, THAT THEY
					MIGHT NOT BEAR WITNESS TO WHAT THE TRAVELER WAS ABOUT TO DO, BUT THE CHILD, IN
					THEIR NAIVETE, DEFIED THE TRAVELER ONCE MORE AND SAW AS THE TRAVELER SHOT DEAD
					THE SOLDIER WHO STOOD IN THEIR PATH.
				-
			-
				Chapter 11 - The Terror: Verse 6
			-
				-
					BUT BEFORE THE CHILD COULD AIR THEIR GRIEF DID THE TRAVELER SEIZE THEM ONCE
					MORE BEFORE SPRINTING SWIFTLY INTO THE PIPES.
				-
		-
			Chapter 12 - The Run
		-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Run: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now once the traveler had run at least one thousand paces into the depths of
					the sludge did they permit themselves to rest for a moment, and they removed
					their hand from the child's mouth.
				-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Run: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And now free to air their grief through the vile stench did the child cry out,
					throwing themselves unto the traveler for comfort, mourning their friends and
					demanding an explanation.
				-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Run: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the traveler, struggling to find the words to comfort the child in their
					grief, let alone to air their own, was cut short as the ground above shook once
					more, and the traveler took the child upon their shoulder again, insisting that
					an explanation could wait.
				-
			-
				Chapter 12 - The Run: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And the traveler was clever, and the traveler was swift, and they made their
					way through the pipes with a cunning befitting of their genius.
				-
		-
			Chapter 13 - The Hunter
		-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Hunter: Verse 1
			-
				-
					But neither clever nor swift enough to elude the wrath of the tyrant, and so
					the traveler and the child were confronted by a hunter of the tyrant's wrath as
					they emerged from underground, whom as it happened had once been a bitter rival
					of the traveler while in the empire's service.
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Hunter: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the hunter, reveling in their newfound power over the traveler's fate,
					declared at gunpoint that the traveler was to surrender and be brought before
					the tyrant, who might yet show mercy if unopposed.
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Hunter: Verse 3
			-
				-
					But the traveler knew what would befall the world if the tyrant learned the
					nature of meta, and so feigned surrender, only to then strike the hunter in the
					back.
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Hunter: Verse 4
			-
				-
					AND THE TRAVELER FOUGHT VALLIANTLY, BUT THEIR STRENGTH FAILED THEM IN OLD AGE,
					AND THEY FELL UPON THE GROUND AS THE HUNTER MORTALLY WOUNDED THEM WITH THE
					FRUITS OF THE TRAVELER'S OWN ARTS, AND THE CHILD CRIED OUT FOR THEM.
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Hunter: Verse 5
			-
				-
					Now the hunter, realizing that they could not return unto the tyrant empty
					handed, took note of the child, and seized the child by the hand as they went
					to inform their commander of this turn of events.
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Hunter: Verse 6
			-
				-
					But as the hunter relayed their report did the child, enraged, and ignorant of
					the true power of the traveler's more unconventional weapon, draw it from the
					sack on their hip, and with it, fired upon the hunter.
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Hunter: Verse 7
			-
				-
					But it seemed, despite the sudden flash that there was no effect, and the
					hunter, shocked, seized the weapon and cast it away.
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Hunter: Verse 8
			-
				-
					BUT WITH THE FORCE OF THE THROW DID THE HUNTER'S HAND FLY AWAY WITH THE WEAPON.
				-
			-
				Chapter 13 - The Hunter: Verse 9
			-
				-
					AND THEN DID THE CHILD RECOIL IN HORROR AS THE VIOLENT CRY OF THE HUNTER FOR
					MERCY DISSOLVED TOGETHER WITH THEIR BODY, AND THE EARTH BELOW BECAME RED AS
