					And the prophet was as a puppet master unto a marionette, pulling a string of
					nerve wherever there came an impasse in the conversation, and in the end proved
					victorious, having gained the knowledge they sought.
				-
			-
				Chapter 40 - The Probe: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Yet, though the prophet had indeed made a fool of their quarry, it seemed the
					tyrant had done the same before them, for there was nothing of use in the
					soldier's testimony, as it was shown that they were nothing more than a blind
					pawn in a scheme that stretched far beyond them.
				-
			-
				Chapter 40 - The Probe: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And the soldier watched as the prophet faded from the vision projected unto
					them, before screaming out silently as the prophet terminated the spirit in the
					flask.
				-
		-
			Chapter 41 - The Drill
		-
			-
				Chapter 41 - The Drill: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now did the sun rise upon a new era for the members of the order, who though
					still children in body, were, as a consequnece of their own wishes, no longer
					so in spirit.
				-
			-
				Chapter 41 - The Drill: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And without warning were the new soldiers in training called from out of their
					beds to stand before an officer of the prophet's army for their first set of
					drills.
				-
			-
				Chapter 41 - The Drill: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And even by military standards were the trials of the resistence harsh, and it
					was seen, that though the child excelled in the classroom, they floundered
					physically, for as the rival had said, the child was soft, their condition the
					fruit of the traveler's affluence.
				-
			-
				Chapter 41 - The Drill: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And though, after too many bruises to count, had the child foresaken the idea
					of sparring with their peers, and especially with the leader, let alone the
					rival and despaired that they lacked the strength they would inevitably need to
					serve in the coming battles, but the prophet warned them not to give up, for
					regardless of their stature, the world would not forgive them of their
					weakness.
				-
		-
			Chapter 42 - The Automaton
		-
			-
				Chapter 42 - The Automaton: Verse 1
			-
				-
					But one day did the prophet return from a convention with their front, and
					among the spoils of their triumphs was the scrap of a training automaton.
				-
			-
				Chapter 42 - The Automaton: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the child saw in this machine another route unto physical might, and so did
					the child repair the automaton.
				-
			-
				Chapter 42 - The Automaton: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And in their foresight had the child, so as to test it, set the machine to its
					lowest power output.
				-
			-
				Chapter 42 - The Automaton: Verse 4
			-
				-
					But upon its activation did the machine charge the child, pinning them to the
					ground, and the child stuggled against their iron opponent.
				-
			-
				Chapter 42 - The Automaton: Verse 5
			-
				-
					Yet as the leader heard the child's cry and came to assist did the child order
					them to stand back.
				-
			-
				Chapter 42 - The Automaton: Verse 6
			-
				-
					And though it took several minutes did the child eventually manage to free
					their arm, and with it, shut off the machine, and cast it off of them.
				-
			-
				Chapter 42 - The Automaton: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And though they stood, bruised and panting, their spirit was not broken, but in
					fact set alight, and in the coming days did the child train further with the
					machine.
				-
			-
				Chapter 42 - The Automaton: Verse 8
			-
				-
					And eventually, through a grueling cycle of trial, error, and growth was the
					child able to best the machine, and so began to increase its strength, that
					their own might rise with it.
				-
			-
				Chapter 42 - The Automaton: Verse 9
			-
				-
					And one day, after several moons had passed, did the child see it fit to spar
					once more with their peers, but this time knocked their opponent from their
					feet with a single strike, and the order beheld the fruits of the child's
					training, that the child's once soft physique was beginning to give way to a
					more toned exterior.
				-
			-
				Chapter 42 - The Automaton: Verse 10
			-
				-
					Now though the child still could not best the leader in combat, they could at
					least hold their own.
				-
			-
				Chapter 42 - The Automaton: Verse 11
			-
				-
					And not wanting to be left in the dust did the other members of the order begin
					to train with the automaton also, and having seen the physical application of
					the child's arts, sought to learn of them at sessions that went long into the
					night with the child as their adjunct professor, and the rival and the leader
					were among the most eager pupils, though the rival would not admit it.
				-
			-
				Chapter 42 - The Automaton: Verse 12
			-
				-
					And whenever asked how it was that the child had come to be so strong in the
					arts, in their humility was the credit always given to the traveler, for all
					great teachers surely have a great teacher of their own to thank for their
					gifts of giving.
				-
		-
			Chapter 43 - The Vengeance
		-
			-
				Chapter 43 - The Vengeance: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as the order continued in their training with the army of the prophet did
					they assist in the war effort by way of labor and intelligence.
				-
			-
				Chapter 43 - The Vengeance: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And one day did the child, using the same scheme they had used before to lure
					the wrath of the tyrant into their trap, delivered the slayers of the caretaker
					into the hands of the prophet.
				-
			-
				Chapter 43 - The Vengeance: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And as all present had seen the slaying of the caretaker, either in person or
					after the fact, did they come to watch as the prophet brutalized the killers
					into submission, and extracted everything their was to take from them, relavent
					or otherwise.
				-
			-
				Chapter 43 - The Vengeance: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And the prophet, desiring that the show should end in a proper climax, called
					unto the children to decide whether the killers would be granted mercy or
					justice.
				-
			-
				Chapter 43 - The Vengeance: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And all present presented a unanimous verdict, pointing their thumbs towards
					hell.
				-
			-
				Chapter 43 - The Vengeance: Verse 6
			-
				-
					And at that moment did the child walk into the room, unaware of what had been
					taking place, as they had been caught up in their work.
				-
			-
				Chapter 43 - The Vengeance: Verse 7
			-
				-
					So, with the duties of judge and jury fulfilled did the prophet call unto the
					child to play the role of executioner.
				-
			-
				Chapter 43 - The Vengeance: Verse 8
			-
				-
					And the child hesitated, remembering the trauma of having slain the scout who
					slew the traveler, but possessed no the spine to rebel against the pressure of
					their peers.
				-
			-
				Chapter 43 - The Vengeance: Verse 9
			-
				-
					And the prophet gave unto the child a perfectly ordinary weapon, and assisted
					the child in aiming upon the condemned, who hung their heads in acceptence.
				-
			-
				Chapter 43 - The Vengeance: Verse 10
			-
				-
					Now even with the gun in their hand did the child hesitate, thus were they
					shocked when the prophet pulled the trigger for them, painting the room red.
				-
			-
				Chapter 43 - The Vengeance: Verse 11
			-
				-
					And all present cheered with a wrathful ecstasy as the rest were disposed of,
					and at the conclusion of the affair did the prophet raise up the child's hand
					in triumph, proclaiming the child's tears tears of joy.
				-
			-
				Chapter 43 - The Vengeance: Verse 12
			-
				-
					Now after the audience had left did the prophet hand the child a rag with which
					to wipe away their tears, and said unto the child that if they were to cry upon
					dirtying their hands in war then surely they would end up drowning in their own
					tears before long.
				-
		-
			Chapter 44 - The Split
		-
			-
				Chapter 44 - The Split: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now after two suns lengths of training, upon the fifteeth anniversary of the
					child's birth, was the order to be sent on a training excursion upon the remote
					and freezing peaks of a vast mountain range.
				-
			-
				Chapter 44 - The Split: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And as the order approached a series of narrow passes did the leader instruct
					the order to split in three, and tasked the child to lead one, and as the
					leader pondered over who was to lead the third did the rival volunteer.
				-
			-
				Chapter 44 - The Split: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the three groups were to reconvene at that location after taking note of
					the ends of each path.
				-
			-
				Chapter 44 - The Split: Verse 4
			-
				-
					Now after several hours did the child's group and the leader's group return
					unto the meeting place, but the rival's group had yet to show, and the child
					began to suspect the worst.
				-
			-
				Chapter 44 - The Split: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And so the two groups waited until nightfall, but still there was no sign of
					the rival's group.
				-
		-
			Chapter 45 - The Avalanche
		-
			-
				Chapter 45 - The Avalanche: Verse 1
			-
				-
					And then, without warning, did an avalanche come crashing down the mountain,
					and the present members of the order saw that it had come down over the path
					that the rival's group took.
				-
			-
				Chapter 45 - The Avalanche: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the child's spirit shattered as they began rambling neurotically regarding
					the apparant fate of the rival and their group.
				-
			-
				Chapter 45 - The Avalanche: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Yet as the child contemplated turning back did the leader rally those present
					to action, and as the child questioned the judgement behind the leader's
					nobility did the same voice that had spoken unto them over two suns ago echo
					within them again, saying once more to trust in the leader, and so, however
					relucatantly, the child did.
				-
		-
			Chapter 46 - The Skirmish
		-
			-
				Chapter 46 - The Skirmish: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as the rescue effort proceeded did it begin to seem as though the child's
					premonitions were correct, until gunfire was heard in the distance.
				-
			-
				Chapter 46 - The Skirmish: Verse 2
			-
				-
					As upon hearing the shots did all present duck for cover, and the child noted
					that the shots came from behind a wall of snow, and unto a valley below, and
					the child, peering unto the valley through their third eye, saw the wrath of
					the tyrant firing back unto the peak.
				-
			-
				Chapter 46 - The Skirmish: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the leader told the child to take their party unto the peak while the
					leader's party would engage the wrath of the tyrant.
				-
			-
				Chapter 46 - The Skirmish: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And as the child proceeded unto the summit did they note through their third
					eye the faint traces of heat of numerous enemy soldiers buried beneath the
					snow.
				-
		-
			Chapter 47 - The Rescue
		-
			-
				Chapter 47 - The Rescue: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as the child and their party approached the summit did the gunfire begin to
					cease, but as the child approached the summit did someone behind a wall of snow
					fire in the child's direction, and the search party took cover.
				-
			-
				Chapter 47 - The Rescue: Verse 2
			-
				-
					But as the members of the party drew their arms in retaliation against who they
					assumed was of the wrath of the tyrant did the child order their part to hold
					fire, and called unto who they knew was the rival.
				-
			-
				Chapter 47 - The Rescue: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the rival's party, recognizing the child's voice, responded in turn, and
					made it known that they were trapped.
				-
			-
				Chapter 47 - The Rescue: Verse 4
			-
				-
					So the child, wasting no time, contacted the leader's party, but not being so
					naive as to make the same blunders as the tyrant's wrath were the letters of
					their communication wrapped in an machine's enigma.
				-
			-
				Chapter 47 - The Rescue: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And the leader made it know that they had fended off the enemy and were thus en
					route to the child's location, and so did the child and their party begin the
					work of pulling the rival and their party from beneath the snow.
				-
			-
				Chapter 47 - The Rescue: Verse 6
			-
				-
					And as members of the rival's party were pulled from the snow did they reveal
					that the rival, seeing the tyrant's wrath ascending the mountain en masse, and
					taking into account the lessons learned from the child, called to trigger the
					avalanche, lest their party be overrun, and the villages past them be in
					jeopardy, and the child stood in awe of the rival's ingenuity.
				-
			-
				Chapter 47 - The Rescue: Verse 7
			-
				-
					But, having been held captive by the weight of the snow had several among the
					rival's party, the rival themselves among them, begun to fade into that good
					night, their blood running cold.
				-
			-
				Chapter 47 - The Rescue: Verse 8
			-
				-
					And as the leader arrived on the scene did they and their party join the
					child's party in delivering the rival and their party from the brink of death.
				-
			-
				Chapter 47 - The Rescue: Verse 9
			-
				-
					And though the deadline of the excursion that night was an unspoken ruling made
					that human life took priority, and though several souls were lost in the
					struggle to preseve the few that could be helped, the child and the leader,
					working together, were successful in pulling the rival from the maw of the
					void.
				-
			-
				Chapter 47 - The Rescue: Verse 10
			-
				-
					And as the rival breathed of the breath of life did the leader breath the
					breath of relief, and as the leader looked upon the rival did the child look
					upon the leader, wondering when it was that they had become so fair to look
					upon.
				-
			-
				Chapter 47 - The Rescue: Verse 11
			-
				-
					And the child pondered over whether the voice that had told them to trust in
					the leader was the voice of the child's feelings for them.
				-
			-
				Chapter 47 - The Rescue: Verse 12
			-
				-
					So, with hearts heavy for the warriors lost but spirits raised for the
					civilians saved did the leader call unto the order to return unto the prophet.
				-
		-
			Chapter 48 - The Dismissal
		-
			-
				Chapter 48 - The Dismissal: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as the order had overstayed their alotted time upon the summit did the
					prophet demand an alibi for their tardiness, and the leader began to defend the
					order did the prophet dismiss their excuses.
				-
			-
				Chapter 48 - The Dismissal: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And as the prophet berated the leader did the rival come forth, taking
					responsibility for the delay.
				-
			-
				Chapter 48 - The Dismissal: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And it could be seen to a discerning eye that the prophet was indeed moved by
					the rival's cunning, bravery, and humility, but as the rival had been injured
					in the affair, and as they had in fact been responsible for the events that
					transpired, the prophet made it known that they were relieved of duty.
				-
			-
				Chapter 48 - The Dismissal: Verse 4
			-
				-
					And the rival, understanding that it was for the best, and with their head
					hung, went out from under the prophet, who though assaulted by the protests of
					the order, and especially of the child, would not be moved, and the rival went
					to leave.
				-
			-
				Chapter 48 - The Dismissal: Verse 5
			-
				-
					But as the rival went to leave, the child ran unto them, and embraced them, and
					the child said that despite the differences between them, the rival would be
					missed, and the rival embraced the child in return, yet then left without
					saying a word.
				-
		-
			Chapter 49 - The Waves
		-
			-
				Chapter 49 - The Waves: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now that night, as the rival headed out from under the order, with no
					particular place to go, did they come upon the shore of a nearby beach, and
					there did they sulk as the sun set.
				-
			-
				Chapter 49 - The Waves: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the rival cursed the child, wondering why it was they had to say such a
					thing at the last second, adding pointless inquiry to the injury of the insult.
				-
			-
				Chapter 49 - The Waves: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Yet as dusk gave way to night did the rival begin to calm, soothed by the
					beauty of a full moon.
				-
			-
				Chapter 49 - The Waves: Verse 4
			-
				-
					But as the moonlight illuminated the number of their birth upon their arm was
					the rival once again enraged, reminded of the unfinished mission they had
					failed, and overcome with self loathing did they seek the release of the good
					night, and their tears melted into the waters as they proceeded into the waves,
					ready to ride the undertow straight into hell.
				-
			-
				Chapter 49 - The Waves: Verse 5
			-
				-
					But just as the rival's head was about to be submerged did a voice echo within
					them, saying "how dare you seek to throw away your gift of life when others are
					yet in need of you?"
				-
		-
			Chapter 50 - KIMANI
		-
			-
				Chapter 50 - KIMANI: Verse 1
			-
				-
					And the rival's foot struck something moving beneath the waves.
				-
			-
				Chapter 50 - KIMANI: Verse 2
			-
				-
					Now the rival looked down to see that a red stream was erupting from the
					seafloor, and so rival, in a sudden panic, dove down to retrieve whatever
					creature was struggling for its life.
				-
			-
				Chapter 50 - KIMANI: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the rival lifted the creature up unto the surface, revealing the form of a
					dolphin wounded by what appeared to be the bite of a shark.
				-
			-
				Chapter 50 - KIMANI: Verse 4
			-
				-
					So despite the wounded animal's immense weight did the rival drag its limp body
					back towards the shore, and once in shallower waters did the rival lay down the
					poor creature so as to tend to its injury.
				-
			-
				Chapter 50 - KIMANI: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And the rival labored throughout the night, cleverly employing that which the
					child had taught them regarding medical matters, and in doing so made known the
					child unto the dolphin, who unbeknownst to the rival was not entirely ignorant
					of human speech.
				-
			-
				Chapter 50 - KIMANI: Verse 6
			-
				-
					And as dawn rose was the last of the dolphin's spilled blood swept away into
					the waters, and the dolphin suddenly lept away from the shore, knocking them
					back as they danced in the waves as the sun rose, and the rival broke into a
					fot of joyous laughter, relieved to see that their efforts were not in vain.
				-
			-
				Chapter 50 - KIMANI: Verse 7
			-
				-
					And the rival stayed by the dolphin's side until dusk came once again, so as to
					ensure that the dolphin recovered enough to set out to sea, and as the moon
					rose that night did it become clear to the rival that the dolphin had long
					since recovered enough to leave their side, and satyed only because they did
					not want to.
				-
		-
			Chapter 51 - The Parting
		-
			-
				Chapter 51 - The Parting: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now knowing that the dolphin for its own sake must leave did the rival bid it
					off, but the stubborn animal would not budge, and so the rival began to chuck
					rocks in its direction, but still it would not leave.
				-
			-
				Chapter 51 - The Parting: Verse 2
			-
				-
					Yet as the rival began to give into despair did the dolphin's pod, who had been
					searching for it, call unto the shore, and the dolphin turned in their
					direction before looking back towards the rival.
				-
			-
				Chapter 51 - The Parting: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And as the dolphin looked back in the direction of the pod did the rival run to
					embrace them, bidding them farewell, and the dolphin responded in its own
					tongue before departing into the sea, and though the rival was alone once
					again, they once again had faith in the justification of their existence.
				-
		-
			Chapter 52 - The Graduation
		-
			-
				Chapter 52 - The Graduation: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as the order began to recover from their order upon the summit and the
					shock of the rival's dismissal were they set to graduate unto proper service,
					and as the leader was made a tactician was the child made to serve dual roles,
					as an engineer and as an agent of espionage.
				-
			-
				Chapter 52 - The Graduation: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the newly minted soldiers of the order proved a wise investment as they
					triumphed time after time in the fight against the tyrant over the course of
					the next sun.
				-
		-
			Chapter 53 - The Trouble
		-
			-
				Chapter 53 - The Trouble: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now as the prophet knew the value of the child's ingenuity did they see to it
					that the child's missions were not extrordinarily hazardous.
				-
			-
				Chapter 53 - The Trouble: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And after one sun had passed was the child sent unto a remote town past the
					mountain where the rival had buried the wrath of the tyrant, so as to scout out
					its politics and vulnerabilities.
				-
			-
				Chapter 53 - The Trouble: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the child, having completed their day's work, and having picked up
					epicurian tastes in their travels, went to dine at a local establishment.
				-
			-
				Chapter 53 - The Trouble: Verse 4
			-
				-
					But as the child mingled among the not enitrely savory crowd was the peace
					disturbed by a troupe of local bandits, and all present were robbed of their
					money at gunpoint, and the child, having descended into a drunken spell, was in
					no position to fight back.
				-
			-
				Chapter 53 - The Trouble: Verse 5
			-
				-
					And the child awoke hours later to find themselves shackled unto a moving cart,
					deprived of their money and of their third eye, and destined for the most vile
					corner of that city.
				-
		-
			Chapter 54 - The Duel
		-
			-
				Chapter 54 - The Duel: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now in those latter days was placing bets upon underground duels a popular
					pastime among the elite, but it was a much riskier pursuit for the competitors,
					for though victory by ringout was tolerated, victory by death paid far more
					handsomely.
				-
			-
				Chapter 54 - The Duel: Verse 2
			-
				-
					And the child, was taken before an arena, and handed over at gunpoint, so as to
					be the night's entertainment.
				-
			-
				Chapter 54 - The Duel: Verse 3
			-
				-
					Now normally the scum of the city would scout one such as the child to act as a
					"dancer", for lack of a better word, but this night did it seem the child was
					to take part in the main event.
				-
			-
				Chapter 54 - The Duel: Verse 4
			-
				-
					So as the child was awaiting their turn in the ring were they told to change
					into proper arena attire, that is to say, something a tad more revealing than
					to which the child was accustomed, but not entirely indecent.
				-
		-
			Chapter 55 - The Ring
		-
			-
				Chapter 55 - The Ring: Verse 1
			-
				-
					Now, the situation being as it was, and being so exposed, might have normally
					troubled the child, they were not so disturbed this night, for in enjoying the
					fruits of their training, they had, though they did not like to admit it, grown
					somewhat vain in their pride, and beyond that, regarding a truth they would
					also prefer not to admit, they enjoyed a good fight.
				-
			-
				Chapter 55 - The Ring: Verse 2
			-
				-
					If only that is what this night was to be, and the child knew to begin plotting
					their escape even as their hour approached, but from such an empty pot of
					possibilities, they could only draw a blank.
				-
			-
				Chapter 55 - The Ring: Verse 3
			-
				-
					And the child was beginning to worry as they watched the defeated contestants
					of the matches leading up to theirs being carried out on stretchers, some
					moving, some not.
